    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Arca sculpturata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_845",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell fat and more of less square in outline, ventral edge not concave. Shell valves pale pink, central section becoming white; ornamented with fine radiating ridges (these are paired when examined closely). Margins of shell with fringe of pale, yellowish threads. Usually attached to undersides of boulders in sandy sites.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_846",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 30 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_847",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_848",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Usually found in small groups attached to underside of boulders in sandy pools, rock crevices or among sponges. One of only a few species of this mainly tropical group to extend into cooler waters of the Western Cape. Details of biology unknown. The blood of Arc shells is unusual among bivalves in that it is red due the presence of haemoglobin (possibly an adaptation to living in lower oxygen habitats under rocks?).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_849",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bivalves feed by drawing water in, then filtering it through the enlarged sieve-like gills. Food particles filtered from the water are transported by cilia to the ventral edge of the gill and then forward to the mouth.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_850",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but almost all bivalves are broadcast spawners.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_851",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Only two species of this characteristic genus found in the Western Cape, the other being the oblique ark shell <i>B. obliquata, </i>which is larger (up to 58 mm) and has more elongate, darker shell (central portion sometimes eroded to white) with a concave lower margin. The shell of that species is also covered with a dense coating and fringe of black fibers, not yellow ones as here.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_852",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 157).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_853",
            "longText": null,
